d01_data <- read.csv(file = "export/d01_data_save.csv")

d01_work <- d01_data %>%
  filter(commercialorresidential == "RESIDENTIAL") %>%
  filter(permittype == "DEMOLITION" | permittype == "RESIDENTIAL BUILDING") 

d01_work <- filter(d01_work, grepl("DEMOLITION|NEW CONSTRUCTION", typeofwork)) 

d01_work$mostrecentinsp <- ymd_hms(d01_work$mostrecentinsp)

d01_work <- d01_work %>%
  filter(mostrecentinsp >= "2024-01-01")

d01_work <- d01_work %>%

d01_work <- st_as_sf(d01_work, coords = c("geocode_x", "geocode_y"), crs = 2272)

d01_work$type <- if_else(grepl("DEMOLITION", d01_work$typeofwork), "DEMOLITION", "NEW CONSTRUCTION")

At the time this data was called, there were more new construction permits pulled than demolition permits for residential projects, according to the office of Licenses and Inspections. This is worth keeping an eye on for the purposes of achieving the Mayors goal of creating more housing to help bring down the cost of housing and ultimately widen the tax base.

There are many ways to measure the difference between household income and cost of living expenses. One method includes comparing actual income to a calculated salary required to not be cost-burdened by mortgage or rental payments. In McKean County, PA, folks have a low cost of living compared to their median income - while the cost of living in Essex County, NJ is actually higher than the median income.

# ggplot(data = d04_work, aes(x = medyrbuiltE, y = pcentnonwhite)) + 
#   geom_hex()

Lead pipes have very detrimental effects on the health and wellbeing of residents in old cities like Philadelphia. Studies have repeatedly shown that people of color and those who live in homes built prior to anti-lead pipe laws in the 1970s are especially at risk for the demonstrated ill effects. This map examines every Census Tract in Philadelphia County to determine if the area was majority non-White AND if the median construction year of homes there was older than 1970. The hex map reveals a density of tracts in West and South Philly that mark TRUE for that combined factor.

d05_data <- read.csv(file = "data/d05_source.csv")

map_counties <- counties() %>%
  st_transform(crs = 5070) 
d05_work <- d05_data %>%
  filter(Workers.in.Commuting.Flow > MOE) %>%
  drop_na(W.County.FIPS.Code) %>%
  mutate(R.GEOID = (1000 * R.State.FIPS.Code) + R.County.FIPS.Code,
         W.GEOID = (1000 * W.State.FIPS.Code) + W.County.FIPS.Code) 

map_counties_ctr <- map_counties %>%
  mutate(R.GEOID = as.numeric(GEOID)) %>% 
  st_centroid() %>%
  dplyr::select(R.GEOID) 

map_counties_ctr <- tidyr::extract(map_counties_ctr, geometry, into = c('Lat', 'Lon'), '\\((.*),(.*)\\)', conv = T)

map_counties_ctr <- map_counties_ctr %>%
  rename(rlat = "Lat", rlon = "Lon")

d05_work <- inner_join(d05_work, map_counties_ctr, by = "R.GEOID", keep = TRUE)

map_counties_ctr <- map_counties_ctr %>%
  rename(wlat = "rlat", wlon = "rlon", W.GEOID = "R.GEOID")

d05_work <- inner_join(d05_work, map_counties_ctr, by = "W.GEOID", keep = FALSE)

d05_work <- d05_work %>%
  mutate(distmeter = pointDistance(d05_work[,c("rlat", "rlon")], d05_work[,c("wlat", "wlon")], lonlat = FALSE)) %>%
  mutate(distmile = distmeter/1609.34)

d05_work <- d05_work %>%
  filter(W.State.Name != "Hawaii" & W.State.Name != "Alaska" & W.State.Name != "Puerto Rico" &

Mapping commute routes between residences and workplaces can help inform where public transit would be most efficient and see the most use. Its not enough to simply look at the heaviest commute routes, but it is also worthwhile to compare which routes are longest in order to, again, identify which routes would transport the most people over the longest distances. While hubs like Atlanta and DC experience heavy amounts of commuters who are coming from short distances, its interesting to see that places like Detroit and Chicago have very heavy amounts of commuters, but not from those traveling a short distance.

Day 13 - A New Tool

#Source: https://www.realtor.com/research/data/

d13_data <- st_read(dsn = "https://econdata.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Reports/Core/RDC_Inventory_Core_Metrics_Zip_History.csv") %>%
  mutate(postal_code = as.numeric(postal_code))
## Reading layer `RDC_Inventory_Core_Metrics_Zip_History' from data source 
##   `https://econdata.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Reports/Core/RDC_Inventory_Core_Metrics_Zip_History.csv' 
##   using driver `CSV'
map_zip <- zctas() %>%
  st_transform(crs = 5070) %>%
  mutate(postal_code = as.numeric(ZCTA5CE20))

map_zip_ctr <- map_zip %>%
  st_centroid()

map_zip_padenj <- st_intersection(map_zip_ctr, map_states)

map_zip_padenj <- map_zip_padenj %>%
  filter(STUSPS == "PA" | STUSPS == "DE" | STUSPS == "NJ") %>%
  mutate(postal_code = as.numeric(ZCTA5CE20)) %>%
  dplyr::select(GEOID, STUSPS, postal_code) %>%
  st_drop_geometry()

map_zip_padenj <- inner_join(map_zip, map_zip_padenj, by = "postal_code")

d13_data_work <- inner_join(map_zip_padenj, d13_data, by = "postal_code") %>%
  st_transform(crs = 2272)
d13_data_202202 <- d13_data_work %>%
  filter(month_date_yyyymm == 202202) %>%
  dplyr::select(postal_code, GEOID, STUSPS, month_date_yyyymm, zip_name, 
         median_listing_price, active_listing_count, median_days_on_market, 
         new_listing_count, price_increased_count, price_reduced_count, 
         median_listing_price_per_square_foot, median_square_feet,
         average_listing_price, total_listing_count)

d13_data_202410 <- d13_data_work %>%
  filter(month_date_yyyymm == 202410) %>%
  dplyr::select(postal_code, GEOID, STUSPS, month_date_yyyymm, zip_name, 
         median_listing_price, active_listing_count, median_days_on_market, 
         new_listing_count, price_increased_count, price_reduced_count, 
         median_listing_price_per_square_foot, median_square_feet,
         average_listing_price, total_listing_count)

d13_data_22 <- d13_data_202202 %>%
  dplyr::select(postal_code, GEOID, STUSPS, "22median_listing_price" = median_listing_price,
                "22active_listing_count" = active_listing_count,
                "22total_listing_count" = total_listing_count) %>%
  mutate(`22median_listing_price` = as.numeric(`22median_listing_price`),
         `22active_listing_count` = as.numeric(`22active_listing_count`),
         `22total_listing_count` = as.numeric(`22total_listing_count`))

d13_data_24 <- d13_data_202410 %>%
  dplyr::select(postal_code, "24median_listing_price" = median_listing_price,
                "24active_listing_count" = active_listing_count,
                "24total_listing_count" = total_listing_count) %>%
  mutate(`24median_listing_price` = as.numeric(`24median_listing_price`),
         `24active_listing_count` = as.numeric(`24active_listing_count`),
         `24total_listing_count` = as.numeric(`24total_listing_count`)) %>%
  st_drop_geometry()

d13_data_map <- left_join(d13_data_22, d13_data_24, by = "postal_code")

d13_data_map <- d13_data_map %>%
  mutate(diff_median_listing_price = `24median_listing_price` - `22median_listing_price`,
         diff_active_listing_count = `24active_listing_count` - `22active_listing_count`,
         diff_total_listing_count = `24total_listing_count` - `22total_listing_count`) %>%
  mutate(factor_mlp = case_when(diff_median_listing_price <= 0 ~ as.factor("negative"),
                                diff_median_listing_price > 0 ~ as.factor("positive")),
         factor_alc = case_when(diff_active_listing_count <= 0 ~ as.factor("negative"),
                                diff_active_listing_count > 0 ~ as.factor("positive")),
         factor_tlc = case_when(diff_total_listing_count <= 0 ~ as.factor("negative"),
                                diff_total_listing_count > 0 ~ as.factor("positive")))

d13_data_map <- bi_class(d13_data_map, x = factor_alc, y = factor_mlp, dim = 2)

table(d13_data_map$bi_class)

Many experts say that housing prices will decrease once inventory increases. According to Realtor.com, the amount of housing inventory for sale in the United States since 2016 was most scarce during February of 2022. Per ZIP code in the tri-state region, which areas have seen housing inventory increases and median listing price decreases?

During the study period and within the study area, inventory counts and median prices behaved as predicted - either median price increased when inventory decreased or median price decreased when inventory increased - in 35% of recorded cases. More frequently, in areas across the tri-state area where inventory increased, the median price also increased, which occurred in about 58% of recorded cases.

Several studies show that hotspots for crime are colocated in places where there is little tree cover.
